  "The eye focuses incoming light onto the retina at the back of the eye. The retina contains photoreceptor cells that convert light into nerve signals sent to the brain.": "",
  "What is the total magnification of a compound microscope?": "",
  "M_objective / M_eyepiece": "",
  "M_objective − M_eyepiece": "",
  "M_objective + M_eyepiece": "",
  "M_objective × M_eyepiece": "",
  "The total magnification of a compound microscope is the product of the objective magnification and the eyepiece magnification. For example, a 40× objective and a 10× eyepiece give 400× total magnification.": "",
  "What does a magnifying glass do when an object is closer than the focal point?": "",
  "It creates a real inverted image on a screen": "",
  "It produces a magnified, virtual, upright image": "",
  "It makes the object appear smaller and farther away": "",
  "It produces no image at all when used this way": "",
  "A magnifying glass (converging lens) produces a magnified, virtual, upright image when the object is placed between the lens and its focal point. This is the most common way a magnifying glass is used.": "",
  "What is the far point of a normal eye?": "",
  "About 10 meters away from the eye": "",
