  "What is 'myopia' in terms of eye optics?": "",
  "A condition where the eye focuses distant images in front of the retina": "",
  "A condition where the eye focuses nearby images behind the retina": "",
  "A condition where the eye cannot distinguish different colors at all": "",
  "A condition where the eye lens becomes completely opaque over time": "",
  "Myopia (nearsightedness) occurs when the eyeball is too long or the lens is too powerful, causing images of distant objects to focus in front of the retina instead of on it.": "",
  "What is 'hyperopia' in terms of eye optics?": "",
  "A condition where distant objects appear blurry to the observer": "",
  "A condition where nearby objects focus behind the retina surface": "",
  "A condition caused by uneven curvature of the cornea surface": "",
  "A condition where both near and far objects appear equally blurry": "",
  "Hyperopia (farsightedness) occurs when the eyeball is too short or the lens is too weak, causing images of nearby objects to focus behind the retina. Distant objects may still be clear.": "",
  "What is the 'retina' and what is its function?": "",
  "The colored part of the eye that controls how much light enters": "",
  "The light-sensitive layer at the back of the eye that detects images": "",
  "The transparent front covering of the eye that refracts light first": "",
  "The adjustable opening in the eye that changes size in bright light": "",
  "The retina is the light-sensitive layer at the back of the eye. It contains photoreceptor cells (rods and cones) that convert focused light into electrical signals sent to the brain via the optic nerve.": "",
  "What is the 'objective lens' in a microscope or telescope?": "",
  "The lens closest to the observer's eye for magnifying the image": "",
  "The lens closest to the object being observed that gathers light": "",
  "A corrective lens used to fix chromatic aberration in the system": "",
  "A flat mirror used to redirect light into the optical instrument": "",
  "The objective lens is the lens closest to the object being viewed. In a telescope, it has a long focal length to collect light from distant objects. In a microscope, it has a short focal length for high magnification.": "",
  "What is the 'eyepiece' of an optical instrument?": "",
  "The lens closest to the object that forms the initial image": "",
  "The lens closest to the eye that magnifies the image further": "",
  "The protective cover that shields the instrument from damage": "",
  "The focusing knob that adjusts the distance between the lenses": "",
  "The eyepiece is the lens closest to the observer's eye. It acts like a magnifying glass, further enlarging the image produced by the objective lens.": "",
  "What does 'accommodation' mean for the human eye?": "",
  "The ability of the pupil to change size in response to light levels": "",
  "The ability of the lens to change shape to focus at different distances": "",
  "The ability of the retina to adjust its sensitivity to different colors": "",
  "The ability of the cornea to filter out harmful ultraviolet radiation": "",
  "Accommodation is the process by which the ciliary muscles change the shape of the eye's lens to focus on objects at different distances. The lens becomes rounder for nearby objects and flatter for distant ones.": "",
  "What does 'angular magnification' mean for a telescope?": "",
  "How much closer the object physically moves toward the observer": "",
  "How much larger the angle subtended by the image is compared to the object": "",
  "How much brighter the image appears compared to the naked eye view": "",
  "How many degrees the telescope can rotate to scan the entire sky": "",
  "Angular magnification is the ratio of the angle subtended at the eye by the image through the instrument to the angle subtended by the object viewed with the naked eye. For a telescope, M = f_objective / f_eyepiece.": "",
  "What is the 'cornea' of the eye?": "",
  "The opening that controls how much light enters the eye interior": "",
  "The transparent front surface that does most of the light refraction": "",
  "The layer at the back of the eye that detects the focused image": "",
  "The colored ring that gives the eye its distinctive color appearance": "",
  "The cornea is the transparent, curved front surface of the eye. It performs about two-thirds of the eye's total refraction, bending incoming light before it reaches the adjustable lens behind it.": "",
