  "A microscope using a single magnifying lens to view small objects": "",
  "A microscope using two lens systems for higher total magnification": "",
  "A microscope that uses electron beams instead of visible light": "",
  "A microscope that uses mirrors instead of any lenses for magnification": "",
  "A compound microscope uses two lens systems — the objective and the eyepiece — to achieve high total magnification. The total magnification is the product of both individual magnifications.": "",
  "What is the 'near point' of the eye?": "",
  "The farthest distance at which the eye can focus on an object clearly": "",
  "The closest distance at which the eye can focus on an object clearly": "",
  "The distance from the lens to the retina inside the eyeball itself": "",
  "The distance from the cornea to the center of the eye's lens": "",
  "The near point is the closest distance at which the eye can focus clearly on an object. For a normal eye, this is approximately 25 cm. The near point increases with age.": "",
